  "summary": "During an inquest, David Hunter is questioned by the coroner regarding his whereabouts on Tuesday evening. When presented with a golden lighter found near the body, Hunter claims it is his but asserts he lost it on Friday morning. Mr. Guyson suggests the coroner might have left his own lighter at the deceased's location on Saturday, but the coroner moves on.\n\nCaptain George Douglas Potter, formerly of the Royal African Rifles, takes the stand and identifies the deceased as his friend, Robert André. However, Rosaline Crowd (Mrs. Gordon-Claude) testifies that she does not know the body and insists it is not her husband, Robert André. Despite her firm denial, the jury returns a verdict of premeditated murder against David Hunter.\n\nFollowing the inquest, the coroner, Superintendent Spence, the county police chief, and Hercule Poirot meet to discuss the case. The police chief notes that André had previously planned to fake his death using the name Enoch Yates. Spence expresses concern regarding the lack of concrete evidence, noting that the English countryside is deserted in the evenings, making it difficult to find witnesses. He reveals that the primary evidence against Hunter is the golden lighter found under the body, though it bears no fingerprints. Additionally, the deceased's watch stopped at 9:10, which aligns with testimony that André was expecting a client. Spence concludes that the only people with a motive are David Hunter or his sister.",
